    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        
            <p>The range of <i>Brassica, Hirschfeldia, Isatis</i>, and <i>Raphanus</i> species includes all sections across California. The range of <i>Centaurea melitensis</i> and <i>C. solstitialis</i> includes cismontane California and the western Mojave Desert (322A), but stands of this alliance have not been documented in the desert.</p>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Aa-l). No description available</li>
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast Ranges</b> (M262Aa-k). No description available</li>
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262Aa-z). Stands of <i>Centaurea solstitialis</i> in Suisun Marsh occur in narrow upland belts, on levee tops. They occupy broad expanses in uplands adjacent to the marsh, and in some cases occur within drier managed areas (Keeler-Wolf and Vaghti 2000). Within a 4-year interval, the acreage of stands increased by 5 ha (Vaghti and Keeler-Wolf 2003).
Keeler-Wolf and Vaghti (2000) recognized sufficient areas of <i>Brassica nigra </i>and <i>Raphanus sativus</i> to map at Suisun Marsh. <i>R. sativus </i>tends to occur in slightly more moist and lowland settings than <i>B. nigra</i>. Neither species changed appreciably over a 4-year period. Stands of <i>Hirschfeldia incana </i>occur adjacent to agricultural fields in wildlands and in grazing lands.</li>
        
            <li><b>Klamath Mountains</b> (M261Aa-f, Ah-n, Ap-r, Au). No description available</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast</b> (263Aa-m). No description available</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast Ranges</b> (M261Ba-f). No description available</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Interior Coast Ranges</b> (M261Ca-c). No description available</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Ea-n, Ep-u). Stands occur in small patches at lower montane elevations, including the Yosemite National Park and environs (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003b).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada Foothills</b> (M261Fa-e). Stands occur throughout the section in upland grasslands on a variety of substrates and soil textures (Klein et al. 2007). Evens et al. (2004) placed stands with high <i>Brachypodium distachyon </i>and <i>Centaurea </i>cover in a <i>Brachypodium distachyon </i>alliance, but we place them here. Many stands contained low cover of natives such as <i>Amsinckia menziesii, Brodiaea elegans, Chlorogalum pomeridianum, Clarkia purpurea, Elymus glaucus, Madia </i>spp., and <i>Plagiobothrys nothofulvus.</i></li>
        
            <li><b>Southeastern Great Basin</b> (341Fb). No description available</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Ba-j). Stands of <i>C. melitensis </i>with other non-natives including <i>C. solstitialis </i>occur in upland grasslands at Santa Monica Mountains (Keeler-Wolf and Evens 2006). Stands included <i>Calochortus catalinae </i>(a CNPS list 4 plant), <i>Dichelostemma capitatum, Leymus condensatus, Lupinus succulentus, Nassella lepida, Phacelia cicutaria, </i>and emergent <i>Juglans californica </i>(a CNPS list 4 plant) trees. <i>Brassica nigra-Centaurea melitensis </i>association stands from Keeler-Wolf and Evens (2006) typically develop after extreme disturbance through grazing, fire, clearing, and mechanical treatments.

Keeler-Wolf and Evens (2006) recognized <i>Brassica nigra </i>types in the Santa Monica Mountains with <i>Bromus diandrus, Centaurea melitensis, Hirschfeldia incana, </i>and <i>Leymus condensatus</i>. Stands of <i>H. incana </i>were large enough to map along the Santa Clara River (Stillwater Sciences and URS 2007).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Ba-p). No description available</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern Cascades</b> (M261Da-m). No description available</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> People have planted mustard species as cover crops to reduce runoff and preserve nitrogen, as well as to suppress other weeds, nematodes, and soil-borne pathogens (Bryant 2003). However, mustard species have become invasive in fallow areas and in adjacent wildlands. See DiTomaso and Healy (2007) and DiTomaso et al. (2013) for ecology and management of the different species.

With active management of star-thistle, it is possible to reduce its impact and enhance the presence of native species. In many cases, three or more years of intensive management may be necessary to significantly reduce a yellow star-thistle population (DiTomaso and Gerlach 2000). Any approach should consider the advantages and disadvantages of mechanical control, grazing, burning, biological control, and herbicides to identify the best fit for a long-term program. In addition, the program should consider preventing new seedling recruitment (DiTomaso and Gerlach 2000, http://wric.ucdavis.edu). Also see the CDFA website (http://www.cdfa.ca.gov/plant/ipc/biocontrol/) for more on biological control. </div>
</div>

    

    

